  "prompt": "When is it likely that the proposed extended maternity leave from 12 to 26 weeks will be implemented for private sectors in India?",
  "response": "As of my knowledge cutoff in October 2023, there is no official confirmation on when the proposed extension of maternity leave from 12 to 26 weeks for the private sector in India will be implemented. The current **Maternity Benefit Act, 1961** mandates 26 weeks of paid maternity leave for women in the organized sector (public and private), but this provision is not explicitly extended to all private sector employees, especially those in smaller or unorganized enterprises.\n\nThe Indian government has been actively discussing and considering reforms to improve women's workforce participation and maternity benefits. However, implementing such changes requires legislative amendments, consultations with stakeholders, and addressing concerns from private sector employers about the potential financial burden.\n\nFor the latest updates, it is advisable to monitor official announcements from the **Ministry of Labour and Employment** or related government bodies. If the proposal gains momentum, it could be introduced as part of a larger labor reform initiative or as a standalone amendment to the existing legislation. Keep an eye on news sources and government notifications for any developments.",
